2 Sec. 3. NRS 289.605 is hereby amended to read as follows:
3 289.605 1. The Commission shall require, as a condition of
4 the certification of each peace officer, the completion of training
5 concerning identifying and interacting with persons with
6 developmental disabilities. Such training must include, without
7 limitation, at least 4 hours of in-person training concerning:
8 (a) The nature and manifestation of autism spectrum
9 disorders;
10 (b) Appropriate techniques for interviewing or interrogating a
11 person with an autism spectrum disorder;
12 (c) Techniques for locating a person with an autism spectrum
13 disorder who is missing and in danger, with as little stress as
14 possible for the person with an autism spectrum disorder;
15 (d) Techniques for recognizing the agency of a person with an
16 autism spectrum disorder while identifying potentially abusive or
17 coercive situations;
18 (e) Techniques for deescalating a potentially dangerous
19 situation involving a person with an autism spectrum disorder to
20 protect the safety of the peace officer and the person with an
21 autism spectrum disorder;
22 (f) Techniques for differentiating between a person with an
23 autism spectrum disorder and a person who does not have an
24 autism spectrum disorder but is acting belligerently,
25 uncooperatively or otherwise similarly to a person with an autism
26 spectrum disorder;
27 (g) Procedures to identify and address challenges related to the
28 safety of persons with an autism spectrum disorder in correctional
29 facilities; and
30 (h) The impact of interacting with peace officers on persons
31 with autism spectrum disorders.
32 2. Training completed pursuant to this section also satisfies the
33 requirement for such training prescribed by NRS 450B.160 or
34 450B.180, if applicable.
35 3. As used in this section, “developmental disability” has the
36 meaning ascribed to it in NRS 435.007.
